   <title>Semantic html5 tags and how to use them.</title>
   <link href="http://tryggvigy.github.io//2014/08/29/semantic-html5-tags-and-how-to-use-them/"/>
   <updated>2014-08-29T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
   <id>http://tryggvigy.github.io/2014/08/29/semantic-html5-tags-and-how-to-use-them</id>
   <content type="html">&lt;h2&gt;What is a semantic tag?&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are a few examples of semantic html tags:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-html&quot; data-lang=&quot;html&quot;&gt;&amp;lt;header&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;nav&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;article&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;img&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;h1&amp;gt;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Semantic tags clearly define the purpouse and meaning of content inside of them.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;h5&gt;In the codepen below is an example of semantic html code:&lt;/h5&gt;

&lt;p data-height=&quot;268&quot; data-theme-id=&quot;8166&quot; data-slug-hash=&quot;qkEbt&quot; data-default-tab=&quot;result&quot; class='codepen'&gt;See the Pen &lt;a href='http://codepen.io/tryggvigy/pen/qkEbt/'&gt;qkEbt&lt;/a&gt; by Tryggvi Gylfason (&lt;a href='http://codepen.io/tryggvigy'&gt;@tryggvigy&lt;/a&gt;) on &lt;a href='http://codepen.io'&gt;CodePen&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;script async src=&quot;//codepen.io/assets/embed/ei.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;So what is NOT semantic HTML code?&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-html&quot; data-lang=&quot;html&quot;&gt;&amp;lt;div&amp;gt;, &amp;lt;span&amp;gt;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Some tags do not &amp;quot;tell&amp;quot; you anything about the content inside of them, these tags are &amp;quot;non-semantic&amp;quot;
or &amp;quot;presentation only&amp;quot; tags.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;There is nothing &lt;em&gt;wrong&lt;/em&gt; with using these tags and infact can often be very useful and are widely used.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;The reasoning behind using semantic HTML tags is to
avoid &amp;quot;div-hell&amp;quot; on webpages.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Lessons learned&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Think twice about the tags you use.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When writing HTML, try to use the tag that makes the most sence. This will make your code more readable.&lt;/p&gt;

